          "body": "The judicial pivot arrives at verse 11: 'Behold, I am bringing disaster on them which they will not be able to escape.' The inescapability is the text's sharpest word — flight, diplomacy, and prayer are all foreclosed. When disaster comes, Judah will cry to the LORD, but He will not listen (11:11). They will then turn to the gods they have been serving, but those gods 'surely will not save them in the time of their disaster' (11:12). The double failure — the LORD silent, the idols impotent — is the chapter's most devastating pastoral point. Idolatry is not merely morally wrong; it is strategically catastrophic. The gods Judah chose as alternatives to Yahweh provide no protection in the crisis they were supposed to prevent. The same logic drives the prohibition of verse 14: Jeremiah himself is forbidden to intercede. This is not indifference but judicial finality. The sentence has been passed; the court is no longer receiving petitions. Three times in Jeremiah (7:16; 11:14; 14:11), God restrains the prophet's intercession — each time marking a threshold where the covenant's curse clauses have fully activated."
