          "title": "The olive tree — election's beauty, judgment's fire",
          "body": "Verses 15-17 form a lyrical interlude between the national lawsuit and the prophet's personal crisis. God addresses Israel as 'My beloved' (*yedid*, 11:15) — a term of covenant intimacy used of Solomon in Psalm 127:2 and of Israel in Isaiah 5:1 (the 'beloved' in the song of the vineyard). The olive tree image amplifies this: 'The LORD called your name, a green olive tree, beautiful in fruit and form' (11:16). The olive tree was Israel's most prized agricultural symbol — long-lived, oil-producing, beautiful. God named Israel this. Election was not merely legal status but aesthetic delight. The abruptness of the turn is therefore all the more devastating: 'With the noise of a great tumult He has kindled fire on it, and its branches are worthless' (11:16). The same LORD who planted it has decreed disaster against it (11:17). The chapter will not allow sentimentality about Israel's elect status to mitigate the reality of covenant consequences. Calvin notes on this passage that God's delight in His people makes their defection a personal wound, not merely a juridical infraction — which is why the language shifts from courtroom to lament."
