          "body": "The chapter's closing movement (11:18-23) introduces what scholars call the first of Jeremiah's 'confessions' — raw, personal laments that appear nowhere else in the prophetic corpus at this depth of interiority. Jeremiah learns of a plot against his life: the men of his hometown Anathoth, likely including priestly relatives who resented his covenant preaching, planned to 'destroy the tree with its fruit' (11:19) — meaning kill the prophet and obliterate his words with him. The image is deliberately ironic: Jeremiah has just been speaking of Israel as an olive tree facing God's fire (11:16); now he himself is a tree under threat of felling. More striking still is his self-description: 'I was like a gentle lamb led to the slaughter; and I did not know' (11:19). The lamb imagery here prefigures Isaiah 53:7 with remarkable precision — the Suffering Servant who is silent before His shearers. The apostolic application to Christ is not eisegesis but the canonical trajectory of the text. Jeremiah, the prophet who suffers for faithfully delivering the covenant word to a covenant-breaking people, becomes a type whose fulfillment is the Word made flesh."
